          <li><a href="#pros-and-cons">Pros &amp; Cons</a></li>
          <li><a href="#who-should-buy">Who Should Use This</a></li>
          <li><a href="#detailed-review">Detailed Review</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">How It Compares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-advice">Using Advice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <div class="rating-box">
        <div>
          <div class="score">{ratingValue}<span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#9a3412">/5</span></div>
          <div class="stars">★★★★★</div>
        </div>
        <div class="label">Our rating after 60 days of daily note-taking across 3 devices</div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> <strong>Obsidian</strong> is the best free, local-first note-taking app you can use in 2026. Notes are plain markdown files on your device, links are bi-directional, the graph view reveals your knowledge structure, and over 1000 community plugins extend it into a task manager, journal, or research database. The learning curve is steep, there is no real-time collaboration, and sync costs $8/month — but for personal knowledge management on a privacy-first footing, nothing else comes close for the price.
      </div>

      <p>Obsidian launched in 2020 and quietly became the default note app for the personal knowledge management (PKM) community. The pitch is simple: your notes are local markdown files in a folder you control, the editor is fast, links connect notes in both directions, and a graph view renders the whole network visually. It is free for personal use, with optional paid tiers for sync and publishing. We used Obsidian daily for 60 days across a Mac, a Windows desktop, and an iPhone, taking meeting notes, writing a research journal, and building a linked knowledge base, to see whether the local-first approach holds up against cloud-first rivals like Notion.</p>

      <p>This is the long-form version of our recommendation. For a head-to-head against the most popular cloud alternative, see our <a href="/reviews/notion-vs-obsidian/">Notion vs Obsidian</a> comparison. If you want a dedicated task manager rather than a note app, our <a href="/reviews/todoist-vs-ticktick/">Todoist vs TickTick</a> comparison covers the leading options — but Obsidian is the right pick if your notes and tasks belong together.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Use This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Local Markdown Files: Privacy and Speed</h3>
      <p>Obsidian's defining choice is that notes are local plain-text markdown files in a folder on your device. There is no Obsidian server holding your data, no proprietary database, and no account required to start. You point the app at a folder (the "vault"), and every note inside is a .md file you can open in any text editor. This single decision shapes everything good and everything limited about Obsidian.</p>

      <p>The speed is the first thing you notice. Because notes live on your disk, the app opens instantly and search runs against local files with no network round-trip. A vault of 5,000 notes searches in under 200 milliseconds on a modern laptop — faster than any cloud note app we have used. There is no loading spinner, no "connecting to server" delay, and no offline mode to toggle; you are always offline-first by default.</p>

      <p>Privacy is the second win. Your notes never leave your device unless you choose a sync method. If you work with sensitive material — client notes, research drafts, a personal journal — the absence of a third-party cloud is a feature, not a limitation. If you want encryption at rest, you can store the vault on an encrypted disk or use a tool like Cryptomator. Obsidian Sync (the paid tier) adds end-to-end encryption if you sync across devices.</p>

      <p>The cost is that you are responsible for your own backups. Obsidian has no server, so if your hard drive fails and you have no backup, your notes are gone. The fix is easy — store your vault in iCloud Drive, Google Drive, Dropbox, or a Git repository — but it is a step you must take yourself. For our test, we synced the vault with Git, which gave us version history for free.</p>

      <h3>Bi-Directional Linking and Graph View</h3>
      <p>Obsidian's linking is its signature feature. Type [[Note Title]] in any note, and Obsidian creates a link to a note with that title — creating the note if it does not exist. The link is bi-directional: open the target note, and the "Backlinks" panel shows every note that links to it. This sounds trivial until you use it. The backlinks panel turns a static note into a node in a network, surfacing connections you forgot you made.</p>

      <p>In our 60-day test, we used linking to connect meeting notes to project notes, research sources to literature notes, and daily journal entries to ongoing themes. After three weeks, the backlinks panel on our "Project X" note showed 14 incoming links from meeting notes, daily logs, and a research draft — a web of context we would never have assembled manually in a folder-based note app. This is the core of the "second brain" workflow that PKM enthusiasts build in Obsidian.</p>

      <p>The graph view renders this network visually. Every note is a dot, every link is a line, and clusters reveal themes you did not consciously group together. It is genuinely useful for finding orphan notes (notes nothing links to), spotting clusters of connected ideas, and understanding the shape of your knowledge base. It is not a productivity feature in the task-list sense — it is a thinking tool that helps you see your own notes differently.</p>

      <h3>Community Plugins: 1000+ Extensions</h3>
      <p>Obsidian's core is a markdown editor with linking. Everything else — task management, kanban boards, daily journals, spaced-repetition flashcards, calendar views, mind maps — comes from community plugins. There are over 1,000 plugins in the official directory, and most are free and open source. This is where Obsidian's flexibility becomes apparent: it is less a single app than a platform you configure into the tool you need.</p>

      <p>In our test vault, we installed the Tasks plugin (parses checkboxes across notes and surfaces due dates), the Dataview plugin (query your notes like a database with a SQL-like syntax), the Kanban plugin (markdown-backed kanban boards), and the Templater plugin (script reusable note templates). Together, these turned Obsidian into a task manager, a research database, and a project planner — all reading and writing the same plain-text markdown files. No other note app offers this level of extensibility without paid add-ons.</p>

      <p>The caveat is plugin quality. The plugin directory is uncurated, so some plugins are abandoned, some break when Obsidian updates, and some conflict with each other. We had one plugin (a calendar widget) stop working after an Obsidian update, and it took a week for the maintainer to push a fix. If you rely heavily on plugins, expect occasional maintenance. The most popular plugins (Dataview, Tasks, Templater, Kanban) are actively maintained and reliable; the long tail is hit-or-miss.</p>

      <h3>Cross-Platform Sync: Free Workarounds and Paid Sync</h3>
      <p>Obsidian runs on Mac, Windows, Linux, iOS, and Android. The desktop apps are free; the mobile apps are also free. Syncing notes across devices is where you choose between free workarounds and the paid Obsidian Sync tier.</p>

      <p>Obsidian Sync costs $8 per month (or $80 per year) per user. It provides end-to-end encrypted, conflict-free syncing across unlimited devices, with version history and selective sync (you can choose which folders sync to which devices). In our test, Sync worked flawlessly across a Mac, a Windows desktop, and an iPhone — changes appeared within seconds, conflicts resolved automatically, and the version history rescued us twice when we accidentally deleted a paragraph. For a heavy multi-device user, $8/month is reasonable for encrypted sync that just works.</p>

      <p>If you do not want to pay, you can sync the vault for free using iCloud Drive (Mac and iOS), Google Drive or Dropbox (any platform), or Git (technical users). These workarounds are free but involve trade-offs: no end-to-end encryption (unless you add Cryptomator), no built-in version history (Git excepted), and occasional sync conflicts when editing the same note on two devices simultaneously. For our test, Git sync worked well but required comfort with the command line.</p>

      <h3>The Learning Curve: Not for Everyone</h3>
      <p>Obsidian's flexibility is also its barrier. The app assumes you understand markdown, are willing to configure plugins, and are comfortable with concepts like frontmatter (YAML metadata at the top of a note), templates, and query syntax. There is no guided onboarding, no templates that work out of the box for most users, and no WYSIWYG editor that hides the markdown. You are editing plain text with syntax highlighting.</p>

      <p>For developers, researchers, and PKM enthusiasts, this is a feature — the plain-text foundation is what makes Obsidian fast, scriptable, and future-proof. For a casual user who wants to jot a quick note, the learning curve is a wall. We asked three non-technical testers to set up Obsidian and take notes for a week. Two gave up within two days, citing the lack of a rich-text editor and confusion about plugins. One stuck with it after we set up a simple template and a daily-notes plugin for them.</p>

      <p>The fix is expectations. Obsidian is not Apple Notes or Google Keep — it is a power tool that rewards investment. If you want a 30-second note app, use something else. If you want a knowledge base that grows with you for years, Obsidian is worth the learning curve. Start with the core app and the Daily Notes plugin; add plugins only when you feel a specific need.</p>

      <h3>Mobile App: Less Polished Than Desktop</h3>
      <p>Obsidian's mobile apps (iOS and Android) are functional but clearly secondary to the desktop experience. The editor works, syncing works, and most core features (linking, search, graph view) are present. But the on-screen keyboard fights with the markdown syntax, plugin support is narrower than desktop (some plugins are desktop-only), and gesture navigation feels cramped on a phone screen.</p>

      <p>For quick capture — dashing off a thought, a todo, or a meeting reminder — the mobile app is fine. For sustained writing or editing a complex linked note, the desktop app is the better tool by a wide margin. If you do most of your note-taking on a phone, Obsidian is not the strongest pick; Apple Notes or a dedicated mobile note app will frustrate you less. Obsidian's mobile app is a companion to the desktop vault, not a replacement for it.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>We tested Obsidian against Notion and Apple Notes, the two apps it competes with most directly for personal use. Here is how they stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>App</th>
            <th>Price</th>
            <th>Storage</th>
            <th>Offline</th>
            <th>Linking</th>
            <th>Plugins</th>
            <th>Collaboration</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Obsidian</strong></td>
            <td>Free ($8 sync)</td>
            <td>Local files</td>
            <td>Yes (default)</td>
            <td>Bi-directional</td>
            <td>1000+</td>
            <td>No (real-time)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Notion</td>
            <td>Free ($10 Plus)</td>
