      <p><strong>Notion</strong> is Obsidian's most direct rival and the better choice for teams and cloud-first workflows. Notion stores notes in its cloud, offers real-time collaboration, and has a polished WYSIWYG editor that hides the complexity Obsidian exposes. The trade-offs are speed (Notion is slower, especially offline), data ownership (your notes live in Notion's database, not as files you control), and extensibility (Notion's API is capable but not as deep as Obsidian's plugin ecosystem). See our <a href="/reviews/notion-vs-obsidian/">Notion vs Obsidian</a> comparison for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p><strong>Apple Notes</strong> is the simplest option and the right pick if you want zero setup. It syncs across Apple devices via iCloud, supports basic rich text, and requires no configuration. It has no linking, no plugins, and no graph view — but for jotting a quick note and finding it later, it is hard to beat. If Obsidian feels like too much, Apple Notes is the downgrade that will not frustrate you.</p>

      <p>If you want a dedicated task manager rather than a note app, our <a href="/reviews/todoist-vs-ticktick/">Todoist vs TickTick</a> comparison covers the leading options. Obsidian can do task management with plugins, but a dedicated app is simpler if tasks are your main need.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Using Advice</h2>
      <p>Download Obsidian for free if you want a local-first, privacy-respecting note app that you can grow into over years. The desktop apps cost nothing, never expire, and the core features (markdown editing, bi-directional linking, graph view, search) are all free. You can use it indefinitely without paying.</p>

      <p>Start with the core app and the Daily Notes core plugin. Do not install community plugins on day one — the plugin directory is overwhelming and most new users do not need them yet. After a week of daily use, add plugins only when you feel a specific need: Tasks for to-dos, Dataview for queries, Templater for reusable note structures, Kanban for project boards. This staged approach avoids the configuration paralysis that derails new users.</p>

      <p>Decide your sync strategy early. If you will use Obsidian on multiple devices and want encrypted sync with version history, Obsidian Sync at $8/month is the frictionless choice. If you are technical and want free sync, use Git (with a private GitHub or GitLab repo) or iCloud Drive. Do not leave your vault unsynced — a single-device vault is one hard-drive failure away from data loss, and Obsidian has no server-side backup.</p>

      <p>Skip Obsidian if you need real-time collaboration, a WYSIWYG editor, or cloud-only storage. <a href="/reviews/notion-vs-obsidian/">Notion</a> is the better pick for teams and shared documents; Apple Notes or Google Keep are better for casual note-takers who want zero setup. Obsidian is a power tool, and it rewards power users — but it is the wrong tool for someone who just wants to jot a grocery list.</p>

      <p>Back up your vault offsite. Even with sync, keep a separate backup (a Git remote, a cloud-drive copy, or a Time Machine snapshot). The local-first design means Obsidian will not rescue you from a lost device — that responsibility is yours. The reward is that your notes will outlive any single app, because they are plain text readable by any editor for decades.</p>

      <p>Pair Obsidian with an <a href="/reviews/claude-vs-chatgpt/">AI assistant</a> for research help — we use Claude and ChatGPT to summarize sources and draft notes that we then refine and link inside our Obsidian vault. The combination of a local knowledge base and an AI research assistant is genuinely powerful.</p>

